  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This Dryad dataset, supporting a single-nucleus and single-cell RNA-sequencing study of adult stem cell lineages in <em>Drosophila</em> testes, has accumulated 781 views and 247 downloads since its 2023 deposit, and has been substantively reused in at least four downstream scholarly outputs, including multiple peer-reviewed journal articles.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Produced by a cross-institutional team spanning California University of Pennsylvania, Stanford University, and MIT, this dataset underlies research into how germline and somatic stem cell lineages emerge and self-organize within the <em>Drosophila melanogaster</em> testis. By pairing single-nucleus RNA-sequencing with single-cell RNA-sequencing, the study captures transcriptional dynamics across cell states \u2014 from stem cells through differentiating germ cells and their somatic support cells \u2014 providing a high-resolution molecular map of a classic model system for stem cell biology.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset's usage profile reflects genuine community engagement. With 247 downloads against 781 views, the conversion rate is solid for a specialized genomics resource, suggesting that researchers who encounter the data find it sufficiently relevant to retrieve for their own analyses. The associated analysis software has been deposited separately on Zenodo in two linked repositories, giving users a reproducible computational environment alongside the raw data \u2014 a practice that meaningfully lowers the barrier to reuse.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Evidence of downstream impact is already visible. Three biomedical articles indexed in Europe PMC have mentioned the dataset, and at least one journal article formally cites it as a data source via Crossref. The primary companion article, published in <em>Science</em>, anchors the dataset's scientific context, while subsequent eLife publications have drawn on it to extend or compare findings in germline and somatic cell biology. A related preprint also registers the dataset among its cited resources, indicating that the data is reaching researchers at early stages of their own work.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Deposited under open access conditions on Dryad \u2014 a repository with established DOI-based persistent identifiers and a strong track record in the life sciences \u2014 the dataset benefits from stable long-term stewardship. The complementary Zenodo software deposits further reinforce reproducibility. Taken together, the usage metrics, formal data citations, and breadth of citing venues suggest that this resource is making a meaningful contribution to the <em>Drosophila</em> stem cell and single-cell transcriptomics communities, even at a relatively early point in its citation life cycle.</p>",
